    slug: "history-of-makkah",
    description: `History of Makkah is a detailed and authoritative historical work that chronicles the complete history of Makkah, the holiest city in Islam and the spiritual centre of the Muslim world. The book begins with the earliest history of Makkah, including the Quranic narrative of Prophet Ibrahim (Abraham) and his son Prophet Ismail (Ishmael), the building of the Kaaba, and the settlement of the valley that would become the most revered location on earth for over a billion Muslims. The narrative traces the development of Makkah through the centuries before Islam, covering the role of the Quraysh tribe as custodians of the Kaaba, the city's position as a major commercial and religious centre in the Arabian Peninsula, and the social and economic conditions that prevailed in the city at the time of Prophet Muhammad's birth. The prophetic period is covered in extensive detail, including the Prophet's early life in Makkah, the beginning of revelation, the persecution of the early Muslims, the migration to Abyssinia, the boycott of the Banu Hashim, the Night Journey and Ascension (Isra and Mi'raj), and the eventual conquest of Makkah. The book provides vivid descriptions of the major landmarks of Makkah, including the Kaaba, the hills of Safa and Marwa, the cave of Hira, and other sites of religious and historical significance, explaining the historical and spiritual importance of each location. The post-prophetic history of Makkah is covered with equal thoroughness, tracing the city's development through the caliphal period, the various dynastic changes, the expansion of the Haram Mosque, and the evolution of the pilgrimage infrastructure that serves millions of pilgrims each year. The author also addresses the political and social history of Makkah, including the various rulers and governors who controlled the city, the challenges it faced during different historical periods, and its enduring role as the qibla (direction of prayer) for Muslims worldwide. Drawing upon primary Arabic sources and historical research, this book serves as an essential reference for anyone interested in the history of Islam's holiest city, whether for academic study, general knowledge, or preparation for Hajj and Umrah. The comprehensive coverage and clear writing style make this a valuable addition to any Islamic studies library.`,
