    slug: "honorable-wives-of-the-prophet-pbuh",
    description: `Honorable Wives of the Prophet (PBUH) is a comprehensive biographical work that provides detailed accounts of the lives of the mothers of the believers, the wives of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). Each of the Prophet's wives occupies a special position in Islam, having been honoured with the title "Umm al-Mu'minin" (Mother of the Believers), and each has a unique story that contributes to the rich tapestry of early Islamic history. This book presents the biography of each wife individually, covering her background, her family lineage, the circumstances of her marriage to the Prophet, her character and personality, her contributions to Islamic knowledge and society, and her life after the Prophet's passing. The book begins with Khadijah bint Khuwaylid, the Prophet's first wife and the first person to believe in his prophethood, whose unwavering support during the most difficult early years of Islam earned her a special status in the Prophet's heart and in Islamic history. The biographies of Sawdah bint Zam'ah, Aishah bint Abu Bakr, Hafsah bint Umar, Zaynab bint Khuzaymah, Umm Salamah Hind bint Abi Umayyah, Zaynab bint Jahsh, Juwayriyyah bint al-Harith, Umm Habibah Ramlah bint Abi Sufyan, Safiyyah bint Huyayy, and Maymunah bint al-Harith are each presented with care and detail, drawing upon authentic hadith sources and the major works of Islamic historiography. For each wife, the book discusses the Quranic verses that were revealed concerning her, the hadith narrations she reported, the Islamic rulings and knowledge that were transmitted through her, and the role she played in the social and political life of the early Muslim community. The book also addresses the Quranic commandment in Surah al-Ahzab that establishes the special status of the Prophet's wives and the elevated standards of conduct expected of them. The author takes care to present historical events accurately and to avoid the exaggerated or unreliable accounts that have crept into some popular retellings. The character, scholarship, and social contributions of the wives, particularly Aishah's immense role as a narrator of hadith and a source of Islamic jurisprudence, are given the attention they deserve. This book is an essential resource for anyone who wishes to understand the personal life of the Prophet, the role of women in early Islam, and the contributions of these remarkable women to Islamic civilisation.`,
